# Reusable Components

Prioritize existing components and create new reusable components rather than writing custom UI code scattered across screen or page files.

## Rule

- **Check first**: Before writing UI code, search the codebase for existing components (e.g. `components/`, shared UI primitives) that could be used or extended.
- **Extract early**: If the same UI pattern appears in more than one place, extract it into a shared component.
- **Prefer composition**: Build screens by composing small, focused components rather than large monolithic blocks of JSX.
- **Avoid inline-only UI**: Resist defining one-off layouts, lists, cards, or form elements directly in screen files when a reusable component would serve.

## Good

```tsx
// Screen composes existing components
import { ListItem } from "@/components/ListItem"
import { OptionListItem } from "@/components/OptionListItem"

export function MyScreen() {
  return (
    <Screen>
      <OptionListItem title="..." description="..." onPress={handleSelect} leftIcon="add" />
    </Screen>
  )
}
```

## Avoid

```tsx
// Custom inline UI duplicated across screens
export function MyScreen() {
  return (
    <Screen>
      <View style={styles.container}>
        {items.map((item) => (
          <Pressable key={item.id} onPress={() => handleSelect(item)}>
            <Text>{item.label}</Text>
          </Pressable>
        ))}
      </View>
    </Screen>
  )
}
```

## When to Create New Components

Create a new reusable component when:

- The pattern would be useful in 2+ places
- It encapsulates meaningful UI behavior (selection, validation, layout)
- It keeps screen files focused on flow and data, not presentation details
